Uranium, plutonium, thorium, and other radioactive materials can potentially be used as fuel in advanced reactors,
turning legacy stocks and byproducts into clean, reliable energy while reducing waste and supporting non-proliferation. 
Programs like the DOE Fuel Line program allow certain companies to safely recycle and repurpose these materials. 
Cold War plutonium, for example, could be reused as reactor fuel, converting weapons material into energy while supporting non-proliferation. 
Many of these fuels can sustain reactors for years before refueling.



Radioisotope power systems (RPS) have been quietly powering exploration for decades, from deep-space missions to remote planetary rovers.

These systems, which generate electricity from the decay of radioactive isotopes like Plutonium-238, provide reliable, long-duration power where solar or conventional sources aren’t feasible. Key highlights include:
 • Longevity: Decades of continuous operation, as demonstrated by Voyager 1 & 2.
 • Reliability: Power delivery in extreme environments, from Mars dust storms to shadowed lunar craters.
 • Innovation potential: Next-generation dynamic conversion systems promise higher efficiency and more compact designs.

As humanity pushes further into space, RPS will remain an essential technology enabling sustained exploration and scientific discovery.





One of Voyager Technologies’ notable projects is Starlab, $VOYG
a commercial space station being developed with partners like Airbus, Mitsubishi Corporation, and MDA Space. 
Starlab is designed to maintain a human presence in low-Earth orbit and to transition microgravity research from the ISS to the commercial sector. 
It will serve global space agencies and companies, supporting scientific and commercial activities in space. 
This project highlights Voyager Technologies’ commitment to advancing space infrastructure and technology.
https://voyagertechnologies.com/




Leveraging Linux in Advanced Reactors

Advanced reactors represent the next frontier in nuclear energy. While safety-critical operations rely on deterministic real-time systems, Linux—specifically Fedora—can support non-safety functions such as data monitoring, predictive analytics, and operator interfaces.

Implementing Fedora in these layers enhances operational insight, supports simulation and orchestration, and bridges emerging technology with next-generation nuclear systems.





NuScale Power Module Distribution (NPMD) — Lightweight, Fast, and Customizable $SMR

Imagine a custom Linux distribution tailored for NuScale’s Power Modules (NPMs) to handle non-safety layers: operator interfaces, predictive analytics, monitoring, and simulations.

By leveraging Linux and open-source software, NuScale could:
 • Reduce RAM and CPU usage, making software faster and more efficient
 • Fully customize the OS, adding only what’s needed for analytics, dashboards, and orchestration
 • Enhance flexibility and innovation, with reproducible builds and tailored security (SELinux/AppArmor)

This approach keeps safety-critical operations on FPGA/RTOS while enabling fleet-wide insights, AI-driven maintenance, and seamless digitalization.

Open-source Linux could give next-generation SMRs the operational agility and performance they need—lightweight, fast, and fully under NuScale’s control.

Automate routine tasks using cron or systemd timers for scheduled analytics, reporting, and maintenance checks—ensuring timely insights with minimal overhead
